Over the weekend I went with a friend to see the three great trees of California. The oldest trees in the world, the Bristlecone Pine. The biggest trees in the world, the Giant Sequoia. And the tallest trees in the world, the Coastal Redwood. All live in California. It’s a trip that covers desert, high sierra, wet forest, wine country, and cliffy coast. Highly recommend.

My friend and I discussed how important it is to be around people who care about things like this. Not just record holders, but people who want to go and see things. People who spot something cool and point it out. That still have a bit of wonder, unsmothered by life.

Then I came upon this video of Jenifer Lewis explaining my exact feelings (she’s the last slide).

Reminds me of Psychologist John Gottman’s work studying newlyweds and couple longevity. There was a specific behavior that predicted if a couple would stay together: If one partner says, ‘oh that’s a beautiful bird,’ does the other look and respond, or tune them out? Gottman called these moments ‘bids.’ The hundreds of tiny moments of connection that make up a week. They may be small and individually insignificant, but over time they pile up and develop a subconscious pattern of care. Am I heard? Do my words matter? Are we in this together? Or am I ignored? Disregarded? Not to be taken seriously?

Find people who look when you say bird, or get in the car when you want to see a tree.

Moving away from home, and returning home for the holidays, gives the passage of time a fresh slap and shock. You see your nieces get older in jumps of height. You see your old neighborhood get a new Walgreens or new houses... or the opposite, you see classic places choke and close. The home where your grandmother made you donuts, is now without her. Her photo smiles back at you from the mantle. She is in the ground now. Her quilts are as close to a hug as you'll get. Your parents are changing. Which you know is natural and beautiful (to the wise), but no less profound and strange to you.

Few things mark time like the holidays. It's as if the passage of time is a feature of their power. To flag where you were, where you come from, where you are now. Hopefully with a glaze of nostalgia and love. Sometimes with the ache of loss. For those of you who live where you spend the holidays, I wonder how it feels to you. If it is as sharply meaningful as it is for me. It's as if the only thing frozen in time is my mom's plastic tree, and Bing Crosby's voice. And they exist to stand in contrast to the riverflow of change. To remind me that I've been living all this time. That living is change itself. We change until we change unto death, and then change into god-knows-what. But in the changing, we are eternal.

Thinking of Ram Dass today. “Death doesn’t need to be treated as an enemy to delight in life…I encourage to make peace with death. To see it as a culminating adventure of this adventure of life. It is not an error, it is not a failure. It is taking off a tight shoe that you’ve worn well.”

- I wrote this in 2019 and just read it again and it’s so funny how time gives words new meaning. Reading my own words as medicine to future me. How cool. I guess I’ll keep writing, cuz if current me needs it now, future me might need it in a different way down the road.

Are you moving closer to the person you want to be in 2023? I just watched the doc Stutz on Netflix and I loved it. It’s about a therapist and the tools he gives people for better thinking, perspective, and growth. One of his tools is the ‘string of pearls.’ This is basically: keep adding another pearl to the string. Aka one step at a time. One day. One more action. How do you eat an elephant? One bite at a time. Don’t swallow the ocean. Drink a glass of water. Do the next right thing. You don’t hold the whole novel in your head. Just move forward, the next good sentence.

Things I write in my notes app before falling asleep:

What if male dominance and patriarchy are just male jealousy at female creation? Envy at the power of the womb. Men seek to control and create the world because they cannot create life. When Freud came up with Penis Envy… perhaps, Dr. Freud, thou doest protest too much. 

If human beings are the only creatures on this planet with real consciousness, then we are a consciousness factory. We eat unconscious things, plants, seeds, lesser animals, and create babies in our stomachs out of that food, thus transferring the unconscious world into the conscious. Alan Watts said ‘Through our eyes, the universe is perceiving itself. Through our ears, the universe is listening to its harmonies. We are the witnesses through which the universe becomes conscious of its glory, of its magnificence’ …and the Universe wants to experience more and more, and gives us the insatiable urge to keep making more of ourselves.

Resist the urge to become an old timer. 

I have felt it sneak up on me. A resistance to change. It started with my local breakfast burrito. They raised the price and took out the chorizo. It went from perfect to meh. Then, my landlord built a fence around our back porch. For safety I guess. Suddenly my favorite view of the reservoir was bars and railing. Then I went camping up by Lone Pine, and the dispersed free camping became reservation-only-permitted spots. The website boasted that they ‘closed close to 400 campsites.’ I almost cried at the loss. Things used to be so much better. In my day, burritos were eight dollars.

We went for a drink at a bar in Lone Pine, and I asked the young bartender how devastated he was that the camping had changed. He said, ‘nah, it’s good. With the pandemic, we had thousands of people come up here and trash the place. You couldn’t walk a hundred feet without stepping in human shit. They just gotta keep it from getting ruined.’ 

I said, ‘oh, yeah, I guess that makes sense.’

Every change has a reason. And permanence is a stubborn illusion and a losing battle. Get older. Remember what was good. And keep looking for what is good now. You love things from your twenties because that’s when you first figured out how to navigate the world. When that world changes, what you built becomes obsolete. And life becomes uncomfortable again.

Enjoy life like you enjoy music. You can’t hold it. You can’t touch it. You can’t freeze it. If you do, it goes away. You can only experience it. 

That burrito spot used to be someone’s favorite ice cream spot, which used to be someone’s butcher, which used to be someone’s family farm, which used to be someone’s hunting grounds. 

I’m not saying embrace all change. Some things should be fought for. Some things deserve a long slow life. Like rivers, or trees. But Jed, let the burrito go.

I heard yesterday (on Dax’s podcast) that statistically the number 1 thing women look for in a partner is financial stability, and number 2 is intelligence… 

and the fastest way to tell if someone is intelligent is if they are funny. I have never thought of it in that way before. If someone is funny, which i’ll know within seconds of them talking, I know they are smart. The laughter that explodes out when they make some surprising disparate connection between things that shocks with its accuracy. The neurons are so connected that they label the absurd in a perfect laser quip. One of my favorite forms of this is an excellent texter. If you can send me a text that gets a real noise out of me, you’re top tier. I have a lot of funny friends in my life, which means I’m surrounded by the best brains in the biz.

I am almost done done done with Book #3. 

We're choosing a cover now. We're doing final line edits. 

This book has been self-therapy. Examining my relationship with my mother. We disagree about the Universe, about politics, about God, about the law, about the project of society, about so many things. But we love antique shopping, we love a diner, we love true crime, and we love each other. She raised me with steadfast care and unfathomable sacrifice. And I grew up to believe things that wound her. I've basically taken our relationship, our biggest blow-outs, our hardest laughs, and that twisted thing that is tethered love that hurts.... and written it down. So many families are estranged. So many relationships fractured by the ghostly pain of discomfort and hair-trigger offenses. Some boundaries are appropriate. Some relationships should be left behind. But there are so many in that middle place. So many that flog us with lack of clarity, with duty and awkwardness and limping strangeness. What the hell are we supposed to do?

Love is not a binary thing.

If you feel any of that, I hope you like this book. She's coming this fall.

“I just want butterflies. I want to feel that excitement, where I’m worried I’ll say the wrong thing. Where I sit and wait for their text.” 

“Can I give you another perspective on that,” Christine said, reclining comfortably in her chair. “‘Butterflies’ can be another word for fear. Anxiety. You worry you won’t be impressive. You worry that you don’t look right, that you picked the wrong outfit. That you said something stupid. So, basically, butterflies is your body saying ‘be anything but relaxed, be anything but yourself, to win this person. Sacrifice peace for attention.’ Which, in my experience, more often than not, is based on some insecurity or wound trying to be healed. Trying to fix itself by taking the wheel. Excitement is good. And fun. But the right person should make you feel like yourself, but more, wanted, and best of all: not confused.

And remember, you can’t say the wrong thing to the right person.” 

“Damn, Christine.”

Is anything objectively sacred? Is the life of a child sacred? Not to a tsunami. Is nature sacred? Not to the meteor that killed 99.99% of everything on this planet.
 
There is a famous work of art called Piss Christ. It is a plastic statue of Jesus on the cross submerged in the artist’s urine. It was displayed at a major gallery in NY. Much of the art world loved it, but enraged Christians protested. If you aren’t Christian, Piss Christ might be powerful to you, or at the very least, cheekily subversive. And much of the art world has contempt for the sincerely religious.
 
But Jonathan Haidt points out (in his book The Righteous Mind) that if we change the icon, the sacred shifts demographics. Imagine if it was a bust of MLK submerged in urine. I even cringe to write this. There isn’t a respected gallery in this country that would carry that. Why? Because the modern world holds human rights as a sacred virtue, not to be questioned. The ancient world had no such dominant belief.
 
Notice how reading this, at some point, you might have bristled. The sacred’s only two emotions are reverence and outrage. The point is, we all do this in one direction or another. How do we know what is objectively right? If that exists. One person holds that Nature is holy. Another The Bible. Another Ayahuasca. Another a fetus..
 
Right now, the battle over ‘protecting kids from groomers’ and drag queens and trans rights reminds me how ‘culture war’ is just another term for ‘sacred war.’ The sacred lends itself to catastrophizing. ‘This will literally kill teenagers.’ ‘This will doom a child’s soul to hell.’ ‘This will ruin America.’ ‘This is fascism.’ As a gay man who was condemned to hell more than once, I side with the LGBTQ people here. I find that some of the most obvious brain rot comes in the name of ‘protecting kids.’ I also find that most progressive movements are hyperbolic explosions, and do harm many lives. But they do push us forward. Don’t they? Progress is a filthy business. But I’m so glad people got dirty before me, or I’d be married to a woman somewhere, hating her by now for trapping me in a life I thought I chose for God.

I never miss my annual check-up. Why? Because of a Meryl Streep movie.

It’s called ‘One True Thing.’ She plays Renée Zellweger’s long-suffering and loving mother. The driving stress of the movie is that she ignored her abdominal pain for too long (a woman who doesn’t want to be a bother) and discovers that she had cancer, with months to live. Renee thinks her father is the iconic hero of the family and that her mother is a meager supporting player. In the dawning of death, she discovers things were not as they seem. The movie makes me cry.

I was fifteen when it came out and seeing it built foundational beliefs in me. I think we all have movies like that, ones that laid the piping for our first frameworks and fears.

But coming out of that movie I knew I would be the adult who got his check ups. Who caught things early.

There’s something I’ve observed in older men, our dads’ ages, who put their heads in the sand. Who don’t mention pain or glaze it with booze. Is it a generational thing? A men thing? To fear the answer to a question, and so, to avoid the question. The rugged male stereotype of a silent cowboy is so funny to me. Standing tall next to you. Not too close. Looking at the horizon. He’s so fragile, so scared, he can’t look you in the eye and talk about his grief. He can’t let a doctor check his blood pressure.

I have cheap ass health insurance. My deductible is astonishing. If I leave my coverage area, they watch me die and clap. But my insurance does allow me an annual checkup. Head to toe. Lungs. Blood. Heart. And every time the doctor says everything looks good, I sign up for another year of testing my body with toxins. But I listen. I get my teeth cleaned. He always says I should floss more. But I love hearing ‘Teeth look good. No cavities. Again.’ I get my oil changed every 10,000 miles (3,000 is a scam).

I’m breaking generational curses over here. I’m breaking masculine curses. I refuse to live with that quiet voice in the background, slithering, saying ‘what if something is really wrong?’

Society seems to go through a moral panic every thirty years. I think this is because thirty years is just about a full generation, meaning young parents now were too young to learn from the meltdown of the generation before them, and they see hard fought equality as obvious. So this is their first real exposure to tectonic shift: 

1960s: ‘I have nothing against Black people, but I wish they weren’t so loud and aggressive about it. I don’t see why they have to tell us how we can or can’t speak. What words we can’t say. It’s too much.’ 

“The last Gallup poll to ask about MLK’s popularity during his lifetime, taken in 1966, found his unfavorable rating was 63%. This included 39% of Americans who gave him a -5 rating, on a scale with -5 being least favorable and +5 being most favorable.” (From CNN) 

1990s. ‘I have nothing against gay people, but I wish they weren’t so loud and aggressive about it. Why do I have to change the way I speak? I can’t call something ‘gay’ anymore? Why do they have to shove it all in our faces? What will I tell my children? What will come of real marriage? Their lifestyle is inherently dangerous, it destroys families and destroys their own lives. Look at the AIDS crisis. It’s unnatural. If we allow this, people will be having sex with animals soon. It’s a slippery slope.’ 

2020s: ‘I have nothing against trans people, but I wish they weren’t so loud and aggressive about it. Why do I have to change the way I speak? What will I tell my children? What if they come into the bathroom and attack me? Soon, we’re just going to get surgery for every kid who hates their body in puberty!?’

Maybe this issue is fundamentally different. Maybe the activists have gone too far. Maybe we need to slow down. But I can’t ignore what looks like an obvious pattern, and some of us might be quiet in thirty years and pretend we didn’t say things we most definitely said.

Trans people killed in 2021: 57. 
Transmale teen suicide attempts in 2022: 1 in 5. 
Southern baptist pastors and church officials accused of sexual assault in 2019: 380 
Minors killed by guns in 2021: 3597

We imagine fake monsters and embrace real ones.

I think articulating ‘why are you here? what is your purpose?’ is helpful. I think that your purpose can change. But as mommy Oprah says, ‘intention rules your life. You become exactly what you believe.’

As for now, I think my purpose is to live authentically and encourage others to embrace the full and healthy truth of who they are, shedding society or religion’s false bindings that corrode the soul. I want to interrogate what ideas and beliefs are hurtful and damaging and root them out. 

I blabbed about this to a friend on the sofa. I said ‘what’s your purpose?’ He thought for a moment. ‘To be happy.’ 

‘That’s it?’

‘Yes. My family has come a long way. Immigrants. Black. I have a good job and a beautiful apartment. I am living a dream my grandmother could never imagine.’

That’s a great purpose. 

I like the thought that purpose can shift, so long as you hold it loosely. Stubborn direction with a dose of curiosity and humility.

This Oscar Wilde quote comes to mind: 

“If you want to be a grocer, or a general, or a politician, or a judge, you will invariably become it; that is your punishment. If you never know what you want to be, if you live what some might call the dynamic life but what I will call the artistic life, if each day you are unsure of who you are and what you know you will never become anything, and that is your reward.”

Writers Retreat No 2. Where did you come in from? England. Newfoundland. Seattle. Arizona. 

Y’all came to this North Carolina mountaintop and sat with me, wrote with me, watched short films with me, listened to me cry, cried a little too, and left with locked arms and heads on each other’s shoulders. 

I can’t believe how cool it all is. I’ll never forget one of you raised your hand, and said ‘we’ve decided that we’d like to have a Q&A’ and I responded to your clever questions and felt more seen and understood than is humanly fair. 

It’s the early adopters who always impress me. The ones who see something they’re interested in and do it, before it’s proven, before it’s obvious. The ones who don’t ask ‘who all’s coming?’ And instead send you a screenshot of their flight. 

#jedssecondretreat @artoflivingboone and forever thankful for @jasonradical @smroma and @llbean ❤️‍🔥

Over the past few months, I’ve made some amazing friends at @llbean. You know, the clothing company that reminds you of sitting on the dock, on a lake, and watching happy ducks or a sunrise. Aka very my style. But the people there have really mesmerized me. They’re real outdoor lovers. They care deeply about the natural world we’ve inherited. And they believe in me. Just last week they gave all 170 guests at my writers retreat a goodie bag of picnic blankets, headlamps, and water bottles. 
 
May is National Mental Health Awareness Month, and they pitched me this idea: We’re going ‘off the grid’ for the month and giving people resources and reminders to get outside, that spending time in Nature is good for your mind, body, and spirit. Could you be a spokesperson? I basically responded: this is my religion.
 
There’s a myriad of studies that prove time in Nature improves cognitive function, blood pressure, mental health, physical health and sleep. I’ve read between 90 minutes to two hours a week is optimal. Maybe that sounds like a lot to you. But I want you to try it. It’s May. The weather’s pretty great this time of year, especially in the morning. Go for a 20 minute walk first thing in the morning. Wake up with the birds. And if you can go camping, or on a road trip, or raft a river… do it. Push yourself outside this month. I bet you’ll feel better than you have in months. And maybe even start a pattern: a relationship with nature. 

I’ll be exploring all month and I’m very excited about it. My happiest place is outside, under the sky.

Thank you @llbean for believing in me, for doing what you do, and for encouraging us to get outside. Check out their highlight for more tips and ideas for outdoor kikis this month. #llbeanpartner #mentalhealthawareness #nature (also this video feels like my life flashing before my eyes and I love it so much) (also stream @ryanbeatty’s new album)

My new book. I have friends who don’t speak to their family anymore. It’s too hard, or exhausting, or triggering. Some have hard spelled-out boundaries. Others let it drift into an awkward distance of hurt parents and heads in the sand.

My family rifts are a cocktail of religion, sexuality, and politics. But I’m not one to bury my head forever. Oh I’ll bury, but eventually the knots of guilt and delayed closure eat me alive. And so, I tricked myself into facing them. I wrote this book.

I hope, if you feel this way at all, you’ll read it and talk to me about it. Pre-orders really help bookstores care so if you can:

Cormac McCarthy is special to me because I am drawn to someone who is both talented and completely free from the expectations of that talent. He loved the writing itself. He loved his heroes. He did not care for the fame, or the marketing, or the money.
 
I love the brazenness of his writing. The self-serious writing that is almost embarrassing today. He wanted to be like Melville, like Faulkner, and held himself to it. He relished violence. I’ve had to put his books down from a sick stomach. If masculine and feminine are a polarity, and we all live in some middle place between the two, McCarthy’s writing was comically masculine. I love a little gore. I love the unthinking wilderness. I am alarmed by the randomness of tragedy. And yet, if heart is feminine, if wonder is feminine, McCarthy was that too. It was sparse, but hit harder because of it.
 
I love how he shunned the decorum of success. Money was a distraction. He lived in a dairy barn for 8 years while he wrote. Then he lived in a shack behind a gas station in El Paso. “Someone would call up and offer him $2,000 to come speak…” his ex-wife said, “And he would tell them that everything he had to say was there on the page. So we would eat beans for another week.”
 
He was living in a motel in Knoxville in 1981 when he heard that he had won a MacArthur fellowship. When asked why he had so many mailing addresses and was hard to find, he said ‘Three moves is as good as a fire.’
 
He never gave speeches or quotes and he gave a precious few interviews. 
 
I’ve relished every one of those interviews. 
 
I think he acts as an icon for something I want to cultivate. The person who does exactly what he wants, not because it is expected, but because it interests me. The simple fact that McCarthy lived a successful life unfettered by his success, shunning the fame that so many drool for… it tickles something in me. I am not like Cormac. I like to speak to an audience. I love an interview. Mostly because being radically myself in public is an act of rebellion against the way I felt as a closeted kid. 
 
But McCarthy is the North Star of my IDGAF dreams.

RIP with the quarks and stars you loved to study.

Almost every person I ask, ‘what were you like in high school?’ ..they answer ‘I wasn’t really in a group. I floated. I was friends with everybody.’ Like, everyone says this. Was anyone actually in a group? A clique? Or is that some made-up category we put on others when something tells us that we couldn’t possibly belong. Are most friend groups actually defined?

Or, maybe the people I gravitate to in my adulthood were the floaters, the friendly generalists. Kind to everyone. Aware that to be too cool in high school was a ‘peak-too-early’ trap. Or maybe they were perfectly unaware, not so self-interested to over analyze the curious work of being a teenager.

To complicate all this, let’s assume cliques are real…. isn’t that the point? To find a clique? A group of friends with similar interests? If someone has even the slightest energy of excluding you, why would you want to be around them? Find the people that want to be around you. Be a person that people you want to be around are drawn to. And if I always feel excluded, or rejected, I wonder if that has something to do with a poisonous hunger in me, probably given to me by adolescent expectations and some bad experiences wrongly labeled, that I want something that isn’t for me and isn’t good for me. How free would we be if we didn’t want what was bad for us.

I know finding friends can be hard. And when we’re young, we want friendships for all kinds of reasons that are hard to ascertain. To be cool. To be accepted by the people we’ve decided are valuable. To find any camaraderie away from our tumultuous family. But as an adult, I know it starts with being an interested person, and moving into spaces of those interests. And having something stringless to offer.

And cliques, if you look too close, aren’t real. Just people in a never ending tango to belong, and stay belonging.

The most excluding people are probably the most scared.

I’m not a hardliner. I think almost everything is wiggly. But, I have a few rules:

Never venue change after 2am. I don’t care if there’s an after-afters at Sally’s house… I will wind down in the car and arrive tired and what it would take to wind back up would mean I’m seeing the sunrise, which is not my life.

I don’t drink cocktails in collins glasses. You know, those narrow skinny tall cocktail glasses so full of ice that the drink is administered with an eye dropper. I’m fighting. (@margiedillenburg taught me this one) 

I fill up my gas tank before a flight. Coming home to a sad starving car is a bummer. And coming home to a full tank makes the gas feel free. I can’t explain.

I read a book in the bookstore for ten minutes. 5 pages minumum. I’m a language guy before I’m a plot guy. I can tell if the writing will please me pretty quickly. And I’ve bought too many books sight unread and got my coffee and curled up on the couch and started reading and thought ‘this is not it.’ And now I own a paper brick.

What are your rules? I love silly little rules.

A few people have read my new book, and I’m discovering (this keeps happening) that my experience is more universal than my insecurities lead me to believe.

The curse of youth is thinking everything that happens to you is happening for the first time in history.

The book is about the rift between parents and children. About divergent beliefs. About a mother painstakingly raising her child one way, only to see him turn another. And not just drift, but hard turn in a way that feels like a repudiation and a rejection. And yet, we stay. My beliefs hurt her. Her beliefs hurt me. And how easy it might be to just cut it all off, to feel that paralyzing awkwardness and avoid it forever. I know plenty of people who have done this. But I can’t.

What felt so lonely to me, turns out is not unique. As my friends and colleagues read this book, they tell me they have felt every feeling. They know every twist and knot. They know that undying love, braided together with conviction and pain, that perhaps can be ignored but never killed.

Maybe it’s an almost universal question: how do we stand in our own understanding and stay close to family whose understanding opposes ours? And should we?

I write in the morning. If I don’t eat breakfast, I write better, until the coffee starts to make my brain tight and twitchy. Some artists find their flow late at night, when everyone is asleep and the phone is quiet. I do not have that. I wake up with a mind brimming over, dripping, and then I drain it for a while. And at about half full, I’m ready to exercise and socialize and let it fill up again with the banter and bitchery of clever friends.

We were at the beach, I was cooking my welsh cave dweller skin, and we noticed commotion down the way. A man was walking four identical golden retrievers along the waves. He had one of those sticks that scoops up a tennis ball and throws it, and he was throwing it into the waves. The dogs, like a blonde swarm of disturbed bees, were clamoring for the ball and leaping in the water and rolling in the sand. They looked as happy as anything could be. I, possessed and not making conscious choices, sat up and opened my arms and yelled ‘come to meeeee.’ The man walking them, a cherub faced older man who looked like a golden retriever turned into a man by some wizard, saw me gesturing and scooped up a ball and threw it my way. In the moment I caught the ball I was submerged in wet sandy golden fur. Sand was everywhere. Water was on my book. I was absolutely in heaven. 

One of the dogs snuggled with me and wasn’t quite ready to leave. The man told me they were a mother, two sisters, and a brother. He gave me the ball to throw a few times, which I relished. ‘Ok time to keep walkin!’ He said, glad he’d given me a messy slap of joy. 

The dogs trotted over to a tightly wound couple down the beach, and the man was not pleased. He stood up in his black speedo and scolded the dog owner for letting his dogs near them. For them being off leash! The golden man apologized quickly, but with a tinge of mischief, and bowed and threw the ball down the beach and the dogs ran, throwing sand on the angry man. 

The black speedo sat down, ‘can you believe how rude,’ he said to his angry girlfriend.

Why does 35 feel so young? Why does getting married at 24 feel like a child’s folly?

Whenever a friend buys a house I’m like, wow, my friend OWNS a house. Like an adult. Impossible. 

I’d suspect my delayed sense of adulthood was caused by my sexuality clashing with a religious upbringing, slowing my growth by cramming my fullness into the closet for a decade. I spent my twenties imitating rather than experiencing.

But I look around and so many of my straight friends are getting married in their thirties, having kids in their thirties or forties. That was geriatric in the 80s. Now, it’s completely normal. 

I’m forty and I know I’m an adult and I feel like one. But the baggage of life I’ve unpacked, phew, I have just started to hang clothes on hangers and feel moved in. I feel so fresh to be this old. 

Do y’all feel this way? Are millennials delayed? Or is this a better way? Prolonged adolescence is one way to put it… or is it allowing people to find themselves a little bit more before making life-altering decisions. Maybe finding a partner a little later, maybe having kids a little later… you won’t marry the wrong people and blame your kids for draining your youth and future?

Or is modern culture so individualistic, so self-centered, that the cult of healing and self-perfection has cost us family, commitment, and sturdy tradition? Is this trend a coastal illusion and the rest of us are already dressing our kids for prom? 

Are y’all feeling this way?

Ten years ago today, @phillipcrosby and I got on our bicycles in Oregon and left for South America. I lived on that bike for sixteen months. “‘Amor fati’ is a Latin phrase that may be translated as "love of fate" or "love of one's fate". It is used to describe an attitude in which one sees everything that happens in one's life, including suffering and loss, as good or, at the very least, necessary.”

Tattoo it.

Things that don’t actually exist in the real world/ aka things that exist only because humans agree that they exist and cooperate as if they do: marriages, laws, money, sentences, contracts, kingdoms, religions, morality, countries, property, human rights, fashion, and stories. One of the leading theories of what consciousness is, is the emergent property of holding a lot of information in connection with other information in our brains. The existence of all the information and feeling in one system, and the overarching access to that information for use in survival, bubbles up into a floating observer, skating across the surface of it all. Obviously I’m reading a Carlo Rovelli book.

Someone asked me ‘what do you believe is the key to happiness?’ Here’s my response: (Brian McLaren taught me to say response, not answer, bc few people have answers, but I can toss a response)

It seems to be real happiness emerges from an innate belief in your own specialness. That you belong here and are worthy to observe and feel and experience every thing that washes over your life as a once-in-reality consciousness. The background hum of self-love will color every other part of life.

Once basic needs are met, the search for happiness haunts. More money. Friends will make you less alone. A fitter body will be a fitter body. More respect. More rewards. And these things are good, some of them vital in proportion. But these things will settle into a hedonic plateau, and without that inner smiling student of self, all will turn to a new hunger, harder and harder to smell as obvious rewards are ticked off, ticked off. 

Now, how do we do that? How do we feel special? How do we feel enchanted at our own existence? I don’t know. But ‘a problem rightly stated is half solved.’ At least I can focus on the right quest, rather than getting lost on trails that end.

Author @jedidiahjenkins and @nicolerichie collaborated to design this limited edition Elephant Locket in celebration of his new book, 'Mother, Nature,' launching this month.  This locket holds special meaning that speaks back to Jedidiah's book: 

Every parent/child relationship comes with complexity. We grow up and believe different things. We change and evolve and conversations can be hard. But I hope that we can commit to loving each other, supporting each other, no matter what. 

I’m reminded of the ‘Parable of the Elephant.’ It goes like this:  

A long time ago, a strange beast was brought to a monastery of blind monks. 
It was called an elephant. They had never heard of such a thing, 
So they gathered around to touch it. The men each stood in one spot and reached out to touch the creature. 
One man touched its trunk. Another, its tusk. Another, its flapping ear. 
Each man touched it from where he stood. 
When the elephant was gone, the men gathered together to reflect on the wonderful experience. But their stories did not align. One man described a giant snake. Another a gentle monster made of bone. Another, a bat-winged giant.
They became angry with each other. How could they lie about something so extraordinary? Soon, they were shouting and fists were swinging. 
In many versions of the story, the men go their separate ways and never speak again.    

~~~

This locket represents a commitment to love, 
To believing that no matter how different you are, 
No matter how certain you are,
There is a love that sees it all from above, 
That sees the whole elephant, not just a trunk or a tusk.

I put a picture of my mom and me in mine. I wear one and she does too.
We don’t agree on much, but we agree that we love each other and always will. 

-Jedidiah Jenkins, author of ‘Mother, Nature’ / Designed by Nicole Richie

We hope you’ll get one for the family member or friend that can commit with you to loving no matter what.

This week's #WritersRoutine is with Jedidiah Jenkins, whose latest book MOTHER, NATURE, is coming on 11/7! 

Where and when do you write?

I write in the morning and near a window. I need to see the day growing and feel the possibility of the hours to get going. My brain works well in the morning. I don’t eat breakfast to avoid sluggishness. I either write in my kitchen, or at a bustling coffee shop. I like to oscillate between the two options. Focus in my home. Or sit in public and let the energy of strangers keep me charged. 

 
 How do you solve writers block?

 I’m willing to jump to what I’m excited about. If I’m meant to write about something that isn’t coming out, but there’s a different scene or a moment that’s boiling inside me, I go ahead and write the exciting thing. And then I’ll stitch the two scenes together bit by bit. Sometimes, there’s nothing, no ideas and no excitement. When that happens, I go to the gym and I read.

“What's your advice to someone whose parents won't be in their life because of religion?”
Here’s what I’d say… You can't control anyone else. But you can be proud of yourself. And you can model love. You can write them letters. You can send them birthday flowers. You can cultivate your own strength and safety and community and chosen family and feel strong enough to love them from afar and leave the door open.
Let your loving kindness corrode their righteousness.
And if it doesn't, let it nurture your own life.

Here’s why I love books. Because most of us, even if we’d been in the same room, would’ve been too scared to talk to Toni Morrison. Even if we’d been at a dinner party with Joan Didion, we wouldn’t’ve said a word. You probably wouldn’t have spoken to the smartest people in history if given the chance.

And for most of human history, you only knew who was around. The smartest person in your village, and stories passed down from granny and grandpa, that was the extent of your view of the world. 

But we have access to…. The greatest minds in the history of earth. We can know the inner thoughts of the worlds most powerful people. The most famous. The most intimidating. The most exclusive. The most destitute and addicted. The most violent and cruel. You can traipse through lives, bloody dangerous lives, elite snobbish lives, hard-won wise lives.. as if of course you should know these things. Of course you’re right there as they fly or fall apart. There is no room you can’t enter, as a watching ghost. When, in all of history, have we been so invited to the whole world? When, in all of history, could you take notes and collect for your use the thoughts of every person?

I met the most incredible people on tour. And I got terribly sick. Like, the mystery illness from 2018 came back. I was shaking in bed, sweating through towels all night, boiling with fever. My doctor said he’d never seen anything like it. Here’s what I believe: writing about the most fundamental pains and confusions of my life, processing myself in a book that is handed off, takes a toll. Being a people person and wanting to meet every person who cares about my writing and hold hands and drink a beer and talk til midnight… takes a toll. I’ve spent so much of my life ignoring my body and focusing on my thoughts, that sometimes, my body takes over and reminds me of its veto power. 

I’m better now. The moment I got off tour and rested I bounced right back. And I’m reminded of how incredibly rarified and lucky I am to have the job I have. To write about identity and family and finding relationship in the muck. My anxieties around this book, my fear of telling the whole story, manifests in my body. This happened just before To Shake came out. The little boy in me is still afraid to tell the truth, for fear of exile. And the man I am today has to hold his hand, shaking with fever, and tell him it’ll be ok.

Reminder: if you give a book as a gift this Christmas, don’t follow up.

My agent told me this once. He gave me a book he loved and said ‘I’ll never ask you if you’ve read it.’ A book, no matter how much you love it, is personal. What touches you might not touch your best friend. It’s also a bit like assigning twenty hours of homework. I love giving books and I love receiving them. But if I give you a book, I won’t even think of it again. If you love it, tell me and we can lock fingers and kiki. If you read the first thirty pages and it doesn’t land, well, I’ve already forgotten I gave it to you so who cares. Go with God and keep buying books. 📚 ❤️

I want to write a poem everyday this year. End the year with a book of poems. 

I remember when I started writing long instagram captions, reflecting on whatever piqued my curiosity, it gave me this nice little outlet to find the words for my feelings. And after a while, it trained my brain to recognize a worthy moment of reflection. Something would happen, or I would feel a knot in my chest about something, and I’d think, ‘write about that.’ Even my friends got that way. The amount of times @laurenpaul8 has said, mid conversation, ‘ooh that’s a post.’

A practice builds an algorithm in your mind, running even when you aren’t trying. I see the world differently because my mind now wants to write about it.

I want to write a poem everyday, and train my mind to spot poetry. To notice an animal, an instant, a juxtaposition, and say ‘oh, that’s a poem.’
